<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911028-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>911028-0015.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Digital Microwave Corp.:   Poison-Pill Measure Adopted   To Thwart Hostile Offers</HL><DATE>10/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10</SO><CO>   DMIC</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)DIVIDENDS (DIV)</IN><NS>DIVIDENDS (DIV)SHAREHOLDER RIGHTS PLANS (SRP)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Digital Microwave Corp. said that it adopted a poison-pillprovision that would make it harder for outsiders to takeover the struggling firm against its will.   Based in San Jose, Calif., Digital, a maker ofcommunications gear, said it knows of no attempt to takecontrol of the company at this time. But Digital has lostmoney in the past three quarters amid sharply declining salesbecause its big telecommunications customers are delayingcapital expenditures during the recession.</LP><TEXT>   The company reported last week that for the quarter endedSept. 30, it had a loss of $3 million, or 25 cents a share,compared with net income of $3.7 million, or 30 cents ashare.   The provision comes in the form of a dividend distributionof one right to purchase one one-hundredth of a share ofjunior participating preferred stock at an exercise price of$50. Each right entitles holders to buy Digital commonshares, or the shares of an acquirer after a merger, at a 50%discount from the then-selling price of the shares.   The rights are exercisable if a party acquires 15% or moreof Digital's common stock, or launches a tender offer toacquire the company. The distribution is payable Nov. 7, toshareholders of record on the same date.</TEXT></DOC>